	   <a name=101440979841183></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101440979841183><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj>Random comments</span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=146002><span id= >Woonx</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>6 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Feb 22nd 3:30 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Hello fellow shamans,<br><br>	Having played EQ extensively in the past 3 years, including a lot of<br>time in the &quot;end game&quot; (there's no mob up to velious expansion that I<br>haven't killed beside tunare and AoW), and spending more and more time on my<br>shaman (lvl 45 now), I read those forums a lot lately and want to share some<br>info/experience with you. Also please excuse my english, it isn't prefect as<br>I am french. I am also very twinked out, so some of the equipment I talk<br>about might not be accessible yet to most shamans, but they are things any<br>shaman should try their hardest to get (JBB, fungi tunic, good weapons, etc)<br><br>	There's a few points I want to make, and the first is about melee.<br>True, shamans can not dish out damage like tanks, but to say that our melee<br>damage output is meaningless isn't true. With a good weapon a shaman can<br>deal some pretty decent dmg with melee. For example at 45 I use a rune<br>etched icewurm fang (12/19 proc 83 dd piercer) and blight (23/47 proc<br>scourge (procs more than any weapon i ever used) 2hb). I usualy don't melee<br>much while soloing anymore myself (did to about 35), but I'll get into that<br>later. My point here is that while it is not always the best choice to<br>melee, shaman do have pretty decent melee skills and not using/maxing them<br>can only make you less versatile. In a group at lvl 45, if there's a cleric<br>I usualy can stay pretty close to full mana at all time (I like having the<br>opportunity to have my full mana available if things go bad), so after I<br>slow/debuff the mob(s) we are fighting, I usualy jump in and take a few<br>wacks at the mob while I can/regen my mana back. So basicly, by the end<br>game, you can expect your shaman to have a very decent weapon, and you will<br>regret not having kept offense/defense/weapon skills maxed.<br><br>	Another thing I'd like to comment on is the AC versus Wis debate.<br>While I agree that wisdom is a nice thing to have and I try to keep it as<br>high as possible, even more important than your total mana is the speed at<br>wich we regen that mana. So I myself go for AC first, then wis/mana on<br>items. Exception to that rule is hp regen items. While most shamans cannot<br>afford a fungi tunic, imho an iksar ceremonial BP (wich go for about 5~10 k<br>on my server) is a must untill you get can5/torpor combo. You will see that<br>the added 5 hp/tick (or 15 for fungi) that stack with regen spell means you<br>will regain mana much faster. I do very well at 45 with only 157 wis and a<br>fungi. In fact at lvl 38 I soloed a lvl 45 named in stonebrunt (the tiger<br>that drops the monk footpads), took about 30 minutes of kiting and regen to<br>regain mana, but it worked. Killing something 7 lvl highers at that lvl is<br>not something to spit on, and there's no way I could have done that without<br>good regen items/ac (FYI I kited it, didn't even dream about meleeing, but<br>good ac helped me the few times I had to refresh sow/dots or can for more<br>mana). So imho above AC/wis you should look for an item with regen (iksar BP<br>should be easiest to get for most shammies, and if you ever get a fungi,<br>then your set for life (or at least till can5/torpor). When you get near 45<br>you should look for JB armor, nice ac and the effects allow you to keep your<br>tanks buffed even in most mana intensive groups (i usualy group with people<br>that do constant pulling, so keeping up with mana can be hard when you try<br>to buff everyone to the max). JB boot/arm/glove are pretty cheap nowadays<br>and every shaman should try to get them, as they really help a lot to save<br>on mana usage.<br><br>	When I solo I stand at max cast range and I pull with malise line.<br>Immediatly after spell has finished casting I start running away from the<br>mob. When spells recycle time is done (usualy 2.5 seconds later), I stop and<br>cast my best root. Then I go to max cast range again and put disease dot on<br>the mob (I cast disease before poison because it last longer so casting it<br>at start of fight means I usualy will get the full effect before the mob<br>dies). If root breaks from the dd part of the dot I run away from the mob<br>till I'm at max cast range and root again. Then I put poison DoT in. If root<br>breaks I run out of cast range and root again, that way mob NEVER hits me.<br>Once both dots are on the rooted/malised mob, I once again go to max cast<br>range and start Cannibalizing my mana back. Now that I dinged 45 I usualy<br>only put in 1 dot and JBB the mob to death. Sure JBB sometimes break root,<br>but since I do this mostly in outdoor zones I stay at edge of casting range<br>and can reapply root before the mob gets to me 95% of the time. In dungeons<br>(I do solo a lot in dungeons like CoM and solB and guk), that's where good<br>AC/defense comes in play. I have about 925 AC and can take a few hits<br>without a problem while I re-root the mob when it breaks. At 45 using those<br>techniques, I can solo pretty much anything that cannot summon.<br><br>	In groups I used to keep str on all tanks, sta/agi/AC/regen(if no<br>cleric) on the main taunter, and dex on whoever had a good proc'ing weapon,<br>talisman/speed on all melee. Now at 45 (45 rocks!) I can put str/agi/dex on<br>everyone with JB armor buffs (sure they are a little less than the best<br>stats buff, but keeping them on all tanks at all time without using a single<br>point of mana is really worth having 5 less str/agi/dex than the best buffs<br>would give). When all are buffed I make pet and from then on only cast to<br>slow/debuff mobs and then melee/can, I can usualy stay close to FM at all<br>time after that, with tanks fully buffed. I don't have JB legs/helm/BP, BP I<br>would only use for sta buff, since you'd have to kill me in RL to take the<br>fungi tunic off my chest slot, helm a) looks bad, and my little barbie<br>shammie is too cute without helm so I use non visible head piece (tranix<br>crown, also priceless for night vision) and b) charisma buff is meaningless<br>to me, only time I need cha is when I do alchemy, and I have gear/buffs for<br>that, I practicly NEVER use charm animals and only use a pet in a group<br>really, they are more of a pain when soloing IMHO. Legs I would never wear<br>since I have thurg quested legs. So basicly with very little fund a shaman<br>can get most of what I do (JB arm/gloves/boots, iksar bp for regen and a<br>decent weapon), and if you get richer or lucky you can upgrade to fungi/uber<br>weapon/JBB.<br><br>	A last point would be that IMHO, a shaman should never nuke at all.<br>At 45 i think my evoc skill is... hmmm 23 =). Having a lvl 60 mage I can<br>tell you that 1) shaman DD are really mana inneficient and 2) shaman Dots<br>are way more efficient than DD, sure it takes a little longer to kill one<br>mob, but the downtime is WAY less than with DD. In 45 lvl the only DD I used<br>regularly is JBB effect once i got lvl 45 )<br><br>	So this is how I view the shaman class, it's a very fun class to<br>play (although I played 7 past 30 and had fun with most of them), this is<br>after all, a game, and fun should be your priority =)<br><br>Khrana &lt;The Dark Exile&gt;<br>Lvl 45 shamanette of doom<br>7th hammer server<br><br>Artificial intelligence is no match for natural stupidity<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
