	   <a name=10147831078974></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f10147831078974><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=9&mid=10147831078974>RE: Random comments</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=9&mid=10147831078974#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=87243><span id= >Gundark</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>1 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Feb 26th 11:12 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Outstanding post, Khrana.&nbsp;&nbsp;Great information to be given out to many high level shamans, and I'm taking notes on what you say.  Here for the review of Allakhazam's readers is my post from a different message board regarding strategy and some of the problems that face shamans.  By the way, my shaman isn't wealthy or much of a twink, so while I value what you wrote, Khrana, there's no way I will ever own anything worth 5K Plat like the regen items you mentioned. =)  Okay, here goes.<br><br><br>------- Pasted Post -----------<br><br>I've been playing my shaman for some time now.  I'm<br>level 40 and taking a break from the game but still<br>enjoy visiting this thread.  Unfortunately when I made<br>this guy, I had no idea about EQ or how it worked, and<br>so he did NOT get his WIS maxed out at birth, like<br>every other shaman in the world.  Oh well, live and<br>learn.  It wasn't really until about level 15 to 20<br>that I realized that my buffs would more than make up<br>for any kind of starting stats that got dumped into<br>wisdom.  So my base WIS is like 90 I think :(   .  Oh<br>well, that being said, Gundark is clearly the best<br>looking shaman ever, with a bunch of CHA points.  WTF<br>was I thinking???  Anyways, that's not the point.<br>The point is this- I've been able to compensate for a<br>relatively low base wisdom by playing the shaman class<br>SMARTER, not HARDER.  Since I also dumped some points<br>into STA at birth, CANNIBALIZE has been the greatest<br>gift the spirits could have given to this dumb<br>barbarian.  Get your Regen on and your Cann on, and<br>your mana is well under control.  Even with stupid WIS<br>like me.  Have a few buddies that can heal ya up.  In<br>a battle, I cann myself just as fast as sometimes the<br>Tanks lose their HP.  That way, I'm not in the fray,<br>and getting mana to make up for early stupidity.  <br>The only HUGE drawback to having low base WIS is that<br>I cannot solo.  No way, DoT's and Dogs<br>notwithstanding.  Can't do it with such low mana pool.<br> By the way, the math on my mana seems to be that my<br>base mana is about 90% of Barbies with maxed out WIS<br>at any given level.  With all my equipment, my WIS is<br>around 160-165 these days.  Still not the brightest<br>light on the Christmas tree, but hey, whaddyagonnado?<br><br>First Item: Genabalizing<br>Now then, regarding the CANN series of spells.   I did<br>some research on it to find some stats.  <br>CANN 1 hurts you for 50 HP, but raises Mana by 28. <br>Ratio = .56 Mana per HP<br>CANN 2 hurts you for 67 HP, but raises Mana by 36. <br>Ratio = .53 Mana per HP<br>CANN 3 hurts you for 74 HP, but raises Mana by 41. <br>Ratio = .55 Mana per HP<br>CANN 4 hurts you for 148 HP, but raises Mana by 82. <br>Ratio = .55 Mana per HP.  <br>(Yeah, I like math and use big sentences and talk too<br>much.  I also don't use U or 4 or THX or whatever. <br>Bite me.  I'm published on actual paper, not just the<br>internet.  Are you?  THen SHUTTIT)<br>Now wait a minute, it looks like the Cann spells LATER<br>in the series are actually LESS EFFICIENT!  WTF???<br>You'd think that, rather than just increase the damage<br>to your body and increase the mana output, they'd<br>adjust it so the mana to HP ratio was slightly<br>IMPROVED with each successive spell.<br>Hmmmm.<br>Dadgummit, that's a cryin shame.  Anyways, I guess<br>that all the way up through the 50's and to 60, I'll<br>just keep on using the same old 50 HP Cann spell. <br>More battle spam?  Who cares.  More mana.<br><br>Next item: the DOG.<br>There's been some debate as to whether or not the dog<br>is worth having around.  I'd have to guess that a<br>smarter Shammy with more Mana could heal him up and<br>buff him and do pretty well soloing.  But by 34,<br>you're pretty much done with that, I don't care HOW<br>wise you are :)  I like to think of the DOG as a FREE<br>DOT.  Cast him once, OUCH you lose a bubble to two<br>bubbles of mana, but that's soon recovered.  If you're<br>in a good group, he can help out the other melee<br>folks.  He won't ever hit very hard compared to your<br>ogre warrior friend, or that crazy Ranger shooting her<br>Velium war bow or whatever with double critical hits<br>and all that, but he's still there, nippin at the mobs<br>heels.<br>He rarely will take damage, he doesn't do enough to<br>get aggro.  He's a free DoT in every subsequent battle<br>after you cast him.  I find it funny that sometime<br>earlier on the thread people were saying the dog<br>SUCKS.  (shrug) Compared to pretty much every other<br>pet in the game, you bet.  But sheesh, free damage<br>people.  C'mon.  <br>One thing though, keep that mutt under control. <br>Listen to your chanter, and make DARN sure you target<br>the main tanks mob and /assist before sending the pup<br>in.  Can't have him breaking mezzes.  He does that to<br>me and my ENC buddy, I /pet get lost him ASAP.  He's<br>good and free damage and all, but he's not worth that.<br> If you can't control your pet, leave him in the spell<br>book.  I think that THOSE are the people who say that<br>the dog sucks... the ones who don't know how to work<br>him.<br><br>Final Item: Spells to Memorize.  <br>Don't do this thing I see so many SHM do, where you<br>sit down, memorize all your buffs, then massively buff<br>all at once.  You should keep buffs on a &quot;cycle.&quot;  You<br>get a feel for how long your buffs last.  When you get<br>into a group, first thing to do is buff yourself with<br>DEX-- or get a time stamp so that you know when the<br>buffs are about to fade.  I always buff myself with<br>DEX first.  That way, when my arm icon starts to<br>blink, I know that my tanks are about to say &quot;DEX<br>FADING&quot; or &quot;DEX PLZ.&quot;  You see your own fading,<br>refresh it and target all your melees in order.  Use<br>the F1-F6 keys for this by the way, not the mouse. <br>And your dog you can target by clicking F1 twice.<br>Why DEX instead of STR?  Your guys will get more hits<br>in.  Sure, they might not be as BIG as they are when<br>you STR them, but trust me, quantity over quality<br>regarding the hits.  I'd rather have my tank hit 5<br>times in 20 seconds for 50 each time because his DEX<br>is higher, than 3 times for 80 in the same time<br>because of STR.  Plus, if you think about it, at the<br>levels I'm talking about, your tanks have weapons that<br>proc.  They need DEX to do that.  Free damage baby. <br>DEX your crazy Bard too while you're at it.  Their songs<br>will be less likely to end because they can't hit an F<br>chord.  They don't even know that, crazy singers.  But<br>DEX 'em anyway.<br>Then, after a couple minutes (once the mana is back<br>where you started) replace the DEX spell with STR in<br>the slot.  STR your guys.  Do this again with AGI,<br>that keeps em from getting hit.  Might wanna get the<br>casters or clerics too, if you got mana to spare. <br>Sometimes they DO get aggroed, and the AGI MIGHT just<br>help them avoid getting hit.  STA is of course last,<br>for Tanks only (not melees, but TANKS, there's a<br>difference.)  More STA = more HP.  Remember, though<br>you gotta buff yourself so you know when each of these<br>buffs progressively are fading.  Not all at once, but<br>one statistic every three four or five minutes or so. <br><br>AC Buffs or my personal favorite, the Talisman of<br>Tnarg or whatever spell you are of appropriate level<br>for.  That thing lasts FOREVER, it seems, and is a<br>nice little HP buff.  Usually it stacks with HP buffs<br>that other people are putting on your guy. <br>Don't forget the best speed buff you have.  It fades faster, but keep it up on the guys.  <br><br>If you did the job right, you will see your arm buffs<br>fade, not all at once in a bad battle, but one at a<br>time with plenty of chance for your brain to rest<br>between.  You see yours going, hit your guys.  This is<br>my favorite right here.<br><br>Crazy_Warrior tells the group, &quot;DEX Fading.&quot;<br>Crazy_Warrior tells the group, &quot;Oh, never mind you got<br>it.&quot;<br>Incredibly_Efficient_Shaman tells the group, &quot;How are<br>other buffs?&quot;<br>Crazy_Warrior tells the group, &quot;All still there, thx.&quot;<br>Snobby_Palidin tells the group, &quot;Yup.  THX.&quot;<br>Mana_Greedy_Druid tells the group, &quot;I don't have any<br>buffs.&quot;<br>Incredibly_Efficient_Shaman tells the group, &quot;I know.&quot;<br><br>By the way, if you got a Druid, ask that tree hugger<br>to SoW and Chloro your party-- they got the Pack<br>Spirit and whatnot.  More efficient than you.  Any<br>druid that doesn't do this is being greedy with mana. <br> (heheh, one of my best friends in game is a Druid, I<br>just like to hassle 'em.  They think they can buff<br>people haha.)  Let them STR your tanks if you want,<br>but I guarantee you that the tanks will be asking for<br>refreshes all the time.  <br><br>You'll have to decide for yourself which stat enhancing buffs to give which tanks.  Not all Shamans want to cast STA.  That's fine.  It's a preference thing with me, and if I can do it with low base wisdom efficiently using the cycle method, I figure why not go ahead and keep it up?  After all, it can't HURT your warrior, can it?<br><br>So spell slots should be:<br>1: Current Buff from the Cycle<br>2: CANNIBALIZE<br>3: Slow Debuff<br>4: Red-Arm Debuff (I forget it's name at the moment. <br>Make's mob frail though)<br>5: DoT 1<br>6: DoT 2<br>7: DoT resist debuffer.  Usually Malaise or<br>something-- or another DoT.<br>8: Best heal you got.  <br><br>Oh and here's something in the lower levels... if you<br>get into a group where they think you are the healer,<br>LEAVE.  Our heals can't hold a candle to other folks. <br>If you have no cleric, make DAMN sure you got a buddy<br>druid or Pally or someone who has SOME kind of heal<br>comparable to yours.  We are BACKUP healers, and any<br>group that thinks they're gonna tackle the sarnaks at<br>level 23 or something like that with only a shaman or<br>only a druid for a healer is deluding themselves. <br>They better have a 'chanter or two of us backup heal<br>types for crowd control and trauma medicine.  You're<br>NOT a healer, you are a buffer.  The more you buff<br>your guys (and girls) the more you will ALL live.  The<br>more they think you are there to be the main healer,<br>the more trouble you'll get into.<br>Do we never heal?  Bah, of course we heal all the<br>time.  We're there with our best heal ALWAYS memorized<br>just to be ready in case things go bad on your CLERIC<br>or if she's out of brain power or whatever.  <br><br>That's the great thing about us Shamans.  We're really<br>good at one thing (buffing and de-buffing) and a Jack<br>of all Trades in pretty much everything else.  DD,<br>DoT, Heals, utility spells like night vision and what<br>not.  Shoot, I've even been able to contribute some to<br>the actual melee battles going on from time to time. <br>A real Swiss-Army Knife of a class. <br><br>Okay, it's huge, I'm sorry.  But I hope that this has<br>been useful to you in playing your Shaman effectively.<br><br>Gundark Viresdator (Strengthgiver) of Xev<br>Shaman of the Tribunal, 40th Winter.<br><br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
